				\begin{document}$$q_{cv}^{2}$$\end{document} from cross-validation) were >0.92, which suggests that the correction model has good stability, robustness and predictive power.

Machine learning methods have been implemented to process large data sets in many fields. In the past decade, machine learning methods have been successfully applied in the field of quantum chemistry to improve the accuracy of quantum chemical calculations for large molecules. In 2003, we applied neural networks to improve the accuracy of DFT calculations for the first time. In that paper, neural networks were used to correct the errors associated with B3LYP/6-311+G(d,p) calculations for the heats of formation (ΔHfθ)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
